{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01KbhyMwoE1FSJ8W5iUp6L13","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Good, recharts 3.8.1 has the standard components I need: `LineChart`, `BarChart`, `AreaChart`, `Line`, `Bar`, `Area`, `XAxis`, `YAxis`, `CartesianGrid`, `Tooltip`, `Legend`, `ResponsiveContainer`.\n\nNow let me write the unit tests. I need to create:\n1. `src/components/trends/__tests__/useTrends.test.ts`\n2. `src/components/trends/__tests__/TrendsControls.test.tsx`\n\n\n3. `src/components/__tests__/TrendChart.test.tsx`\n\nFirst, I'm defining the interfaces for the `useTrends` hook and its setters so I can structure the tests properly...\n\nDefining hook interfaces... Defining the setter functions and result interface...\n\nNow I'm outlining the component prop interfaces for the controls and chart, where the chart manages its own visualization type internally. Moving into the test cases, I need to verify that the hook fetches the schema on mount to expose available events, loads trend data when an event and valid date range are selected, filters properties to only numeric ones for the chosen event, handles loading states correctly, and applies sensible defaults like counting events daily over the past period.\n\nFor the controls component tests, I'm checking that it renders the event autocomplete, all six measure options, conditionally shows the property dropdown only for aggregation measures with numeric properties, includes the granularity toggle and date range presets, and provides a breakdown selector. The chart component tests verify the visualization type toggle and empty state rendering.\n\nNow I'm thinking through the date range defaults—\"Last 30 days\" should calculate from today back 30 days when the hook initializes. I'll write the test files first, then move to the implementation. For the measure selector specifically, I need to handle the conditional property autocomplete that appears only when an aggregation measure is selected, since Count and Unique Users don't need a property parameter.\n\nLooking at the API, measure comes through as a combined string like `\"sum:amount\"`, so I'll keep it that way in the hook state rather than splitting it into separate aggregate and property fields. the decomposition internally. For the test cases, I need to verify that the hook fetches the schema on mount, exposes the event names, triggers a trends fetch when an event is selected, and correctly derives numeric properties from the schema.\n\nThe key timing issue is that trends should only fetch when both an event name is set and the date range is valid—on initial mount with no event selected, nothing should happen. I'll need to carefully mock the fetch calls to distinguish between the schema request and the trends requests, then write assertions for each scenario including loading states, error handling, and the default values for measure, granularity, and date range.\n\nWriting the test file... Setting up the test cleanup and now thinking through how to test the TrendsControls component with its controlled props. MUI's Select component uses a button/combobox pattern rather than a native select, so I'll need to use `getByRole(\"combobox\")` to find it and check for the measure options as text content in the document.\n\nFor TrendChart tests, the key constraint is that Recharts needs actual DOM dimensions to render, which jsdom doesn't provide, so I'll focus on testing the UI controls like toggle buttons, empty states, and loading indicators instead of verifying chart SVG output. The chart also auto-switches to Bar mode when there's only one data point, which is handled by internal state logic.\n\nI'll test this auto-switch behavior by rendering with single-point series data and checking that the Bar toggle button shows as selected. Now I'm ready to write out the test files starting with useTrends, then TrendsControls, then TrendChart.\n\nFor the TrendChart tests, I need to mock the recharts library since it relies on ResizeObserver and SVG rendering that doesn't work well in jsdom. I'll create mock implementations of ResponsiveContainer, LineChart, BarChart, and AreaChart that render simple divs with test IDs instead.\n\nNow I'm setting up the test file for TrendsControls. I need to be careful with MUI's ToggleButtonGroup since it should work in jsdom with MUI v9, and I'm thinking through what default control state to use for testing.\n\nSetting up default test data...\n\nNow I'm outlining the test cases for the useTrends hook—it should fetch the schema on mount, expose event names, skip the initial trends fetch until an event is selected, then fetch trends when one is chosen, derive numeric properties, manage loading states, apply sensible defaults like counting by day over the last month, refetch when the event changes, and handle errors gracefully by clearing the series.\n\nFor the TrendsControls component tests, I need to verify it renders the event autocomplete, all measure options, conditionally shows the property dropdown based on the measure type, displays granularity toggles and date presets, and includes a breakdown selector.\n\nThe TrendChart tests should cover the chart type toggle with its four options, the empty state when there's no data, and the loading indicator.\n\nNow I'm thinking through the actual implementation—the key question is when the trends fetch fires. It should happen when eventName is set to a non-null value and the date range is valid, since eventName starts as null so nothing fetches on initial mount. The API endpoint will be `/api/trends` with query parameters for event name, measure, granularity, and date range.\n\nI'm reconsidering the approach—the plan mentions debouncing or an explicit trigger for fetches when controls change, so I'll implement that mechanism now.\n\nFor the numeric properties, I need to derive them from the schema based on the selected event name, filtering for only numeric types.\n\nNow I'm working through the measure representation in the UI—the selector needs to handle different measure types like count, unique users, and aggregations (sum, avg, min, max) where some require selecting a property to aggregate.\n\nI'm deciding whether to store the full combined measure string in the hook or split it into separate `measureFn` and `measureProperty` fields. Keeping it as a combined string simplifies the API URL building, so I'll go with that approach and let the UI component handle decomposing it for display purposes.\n\nWriting test cases... I need to handle the measure and property selectors' change events by combining their values and calling `setMeasure`, and I'll use data-testids for reliable testing. For testing MUI components in jsdom, I'll keep it simple—just verify the measure select and property label are present rather than trying to open dropdowns, since MUI Select renders as a button with a combobox pattern and Autocomplete as a combobox input. I've already mapped out the test cases I need to cover, so now I'm ready to start implementing the actual code for the TrendsControls component and its tests.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":705,"cache_read_input_tokens":54887,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":705},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"19b45d90-1ce0-4130-bc08-6d66becae3e7","uuid":"a1e84ce5-1545-4221-9f33-cc8239324008"}
